'''Luke Wright''' (born [[March 7]], [[1985]]) is an [[England|English]] [[cricket]]er. He is a right-handed batsman and a right-arm medium-fast bowler. Born in [[Grantham]], Wright joined [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] in 2004, having spent all of the rest of his career thus far at [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]. He was named in England's squad for the Under-19 World Cup in 2004, and joined the International [[Twenty20]] squad for the [[Twenty20 World Championship]] and the ODI squad in early September.<ref name=ECB/>

==Career==

Wright debuted for Sussex with a century, and has won the Denis Compton medal on three occasions during his domestic career.<ref name=cric>[http://content-usa.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/23460.html Luke Wright] at CricInfo retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref> He had previously represented [[English cricket team|England]] at Under-17 level, and in 2003, he travelled to Australia with the Under-19 team and took a hat-trick against [[South African cricket team|South Africa]], finishing with match figures of 5/46. In Februarty 2006 Wright travelled to the [[West Indies]] to bolster the England A team.<ref name=cric/>

On [[June 26]] [[2007]] he smashed his maiden domestic Twenty20 Cup century, scoring 103 from only 45 balls, including 11 fours and six sixes before being bowled by [[Yasir Arafat (cricketer)|Yasir Arafat]] in Sussex's 7 wicket win over Kent at Canterbury. Although Sussex were defeated in the semi-finals, Wright ended up as the highest run scorer of the competition.<ref name=ECB>[http://www.ecb.co.uk/stats/players/sussex/luke-wright,62,PP.html Luke Wright] at the [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref> Wright has also found success in the longer one day formats, hitting 125 against [[Gloucestershire CCC|Gloucestershire]] from 73 deliveries.<ref>[http://www.ecb.co.uk/domestic/wright-races-to-the-top,14294,EN.html ''Wright races to the top''] [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/6933715.stm ''Wright marks call-up with hundred''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref>

In July 2007, he was selected in the preliminary 30-man England Squad for the [[Twenty20 World Championship]] in the autumn, having been the top domestic Twenty20 scorer with 346 runs that season,<ref name=news1/> and on [[August 6]] he was named in the final 15-man squad. In the mean time, he dropped two short of another century by hitting 98 off 48 deliveries against [[Hampshire CCC|Hampshire]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/6276246.stm ''Superb Wright batters Hampshire''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref> On [[September 3]] it was announced that he would also join the England ODI squad as a replacement for the injured [[Ravi Bopara]] and [[Andrew Flintoff]] for the final two matches against [[Indian cricket team|India]].<ref name=news1>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6973729.stm ''England call up Wright as cover''] [[BBC News]] retrieved [[September 3]] [[2007]]</ref>

